HEADWORD: Hallelujah
<hw>Hal`le*lu"jah</hw> }</mhw>
<pr>(h⟦acr⟧l`l⟦esl⟧*l⟦umac⟧"y⟦adot⟧)</pr>, <pos>n. & interj.</pos>
<ety>[Heb. See <er>Alleluia</er>.]</ety> <def>Praise ye Jehovah; praise
ye the Lord; -- an exclamation used chiefly in songs of praise or
thanksgiving to God, and as an expression of gratitude or
adoration.</def> <rj><au>Rev. xix. 1 (Rev. Ver. )</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So sung they, and the empyrean rung⟦br⟧
With <qex>Hallelujahs</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In those days, as St. Jerome tells us,⟦ldquo⟧any one as he walked
in the fields, might hear the plowman at his
<qex>hallelujahs</qex>.⟦rdquo⟧</q> <rj><qau>Sharp.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hallelujatic</ent>⟦br⟧
